### Geography

Live Oak is strategically positioned within the [Sacramento Valley](/Sacramento_Valley) of Northern California. This region is characterized by its fertile agricultural lands, extensive orchards, and proximity to significant natural features such as the [Feather River](/Feather_River) and the distinctive geological formations known as the [Sutter Buttes](/Sutter_Buttes). The city itself is predominantly a community focused on agricultural pursuits.

The precise geographical coordinates for Live Oak are listed as 39°16′28″N 121°39′43″W, with a decimal representation of 39.27444°N and -121.66194°W. Further refinement of these coordinates places it at 39.274518° latitude and -121.662003° longitude.

According to data compiled by the [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), the city encompasses a total area of 3.1 square miles (8.0 km²), with every bit of it being land. The surrounding landscape is defined by rich farmlands, abundant orchards, the meandering [Feather River](/Feather_River), and the unique, solitary volcanic remnants of the [Sutter Buttes](/Sutter_Buttes).

#### Climate

Live Oak experiences a [Mediterranean climate](/Mediterranean_climate), a pattern marked by intensely hot, arid summers and prolonged, cool, and wet winters. The summer months are typically characterized by abundant sunshine and dry conditions, though occasional delta breezes can offer temporary respite from the heat. These breezes, however, are often fleeting. The region is susceptible to heat waves, which tend to persist for an average of three to five days, with temperatures frequently soaring between 105 and 110 degrees Fahrenheit. The dry season generally extends from mid-to-late May through early-to-mid September, during which rainfall is exceptionally scarce. July stands out as the hottest month, with average temperatures hovering around 96 to 100 degrees Fahrenheit. While rain is rare in July, it is not unheard of for moisture to drift in from the Southwest Monsoon.

Winters are notably long, cool, and frequently shrouded in fog. The period from mid-October to mid-April is characterized by consistent rainfall. January typically records the highest rainfall amounts, averaging between 4 and 6 inches. During an [El Niño](/El_Ni%C3%B1o-Southern_Oscillation) event, this average can surge to 10 to 12 inches, often leading to significant flooding. Conversely, during a La Niña season, rainfall can drop to 4 inches or less, contributing to drought conditions that can extend into the summer. Winter temperatures generally range from 45 to 50 degrees Fahrenheit. The region is also prone to extended periods of foggy and overcast weather, sometimes lasting for two to four weeks, a phenomenon often referred to as [Tule fog](/Tule_fog). Snowfall is an infrequent occurrence; the record recorded snowfall was 3.8 inches in 2002.

