### Emergency Services

#### Fire Department

Fire protection services for Live Oak are integrated into the broader Sutter County Fire Department.

#### Law Enforcement

Historically, Live Oak maintained its own [police](/Police) department until the mid-1970s. At that juncture, the city opted to contract law enforcement services from the Sutter County Sheriff's Department. A dedicated contingent of deputies from the Sheriff's Department is stationed within and primarily patrols the Live Oak contract area, aiming for enhanced patrol effectiveness and a more community-focused approach. The city hosts a substation staffed by seven patrol deputies, a Sergeant, and a Lieutenant. Furthermore, a K9 unit is specifically assigned to patrol the Live Oak area.

#### EMS

[Emergency Medical Services](/Emergency_medical_services) (EMS), encompassing [ambulance](/Ambulance) and [paramedic](/Paramedics) services, are provided by the Bi-County Ambulance company, which serves both Sutter and Yuba Counties.

#### Emergency Services Headquarters

The operational hub for emergency services, including the Sheriff's Department Live Oak Sub Station and the Live Oak Fire Department, is located at the intersection of Fir Street and O Street within Live Oak.

### Business

The economic foundation of Live Oak is predominantly rooted in agricultural production. The city was also home to the Leo Chesney prison, a minimum-security facility for women, situated on nearly 10 acres a few blocks west of the downtown area. This prison directly bordered residential neighborhoods to its north and east. It had a capacity of up to 195 inmates. Originally owned by the [CoreCivic](/CoreCivic) corporation, operations were managed by Cornell Companies, based in [Houston, Texas](/Houston,_Texas). Following Cornell's acquisition by its larger competitor, GEO Group of [Boca Raton, Florida](/Boca_Raton,_Florida), took over operations. The prison has remained vacant since 2011.

